00:01:45.909 --> 00:01:47.200
GARY CATONA: Thanks for coming.

00:01:47.200 --> 00:01:48.060
I appreciate it.

00:01:48.060 --> 00:01:52.390
It's wonderful to be here and
to be around so many eager minds

00:01:52.390 --> 00:01:57.210
who are always willing and able
and interested in exploring

00:01:57.210 --> 00:01:58.580
new ideas.

00:01:58.580 --> 00:02:00.980
My story has been
an interesting one.

00:02:00.980 --> 00:02:04.090
I began with a simple
passion to become a singer

00:02:04.090 --> 00:02:06.566
when I was growing
up in Philadelphia,

00:02:06.566 --> 00:02:11.000
Italian-American family, with
Frank Sinatra and the Beatles

00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:13.010
playing both at the same house.

00:02:13.010 --> 00:02:15.830
And I just developed this
passion to become a singer,

00:02:15.830 --> 00:02:20.085
and it started me on the quest
to discover what a great-- what

00:02:20.085 --> 00:02:20.960
a beautiful voice is.

00:02:20.960 --> 00:02:23.850
And during that process,
it was a very bumpy road

00:02:23.850 --> 00:02:26.680
because I had to
unlearn much of what

00:02:26.680 --> 00:02:29.020
I was taught by my teachers.

00:02:29.020 --> 00:02:30.700
And in the final
analysis, I ended up

00:02:30.700 --> 00:02:33.850
putting together a process that
I call voice building that I've

00:02:33.850 --> 00:02:36.380
been using now for
the past 20 years

00:02:36.380 --> 00:02:39.820
or so that has made
a major impact on how

00:02:39.820 --> 00:02:41.580
people deal with their voices.

00:02:41.580 --> 00:02:44.160
And my goal at this point
is to take my process

00:02:44.160 --> 00:02:47.080
and to create as many
beautiful voices as possible

00:02:47.080 --> 00:02:48.930
all over the world.

00:02:48.930 --> 00:02:52.450
So how many people
here are singers?

00:02:52.450 --> 00:02:55.922
And how many have studied voice?

00:02:55.922 --> 00:02:57.630
And how many people
here use their voices

00:02:57.630 --> 00:02:58.970
in their profession?

00:02:58.970 --> 00:03:01.780
Everybody, right?

00:03:01.780 --> 00:03:03.690
Are you aware of
the major impact

00:03:03.690 --> 00:03:06.940
that the quality of your
voice has on your work?

00:03:06.940 --> 00:03:10.380
We know that we have
a tremendous response

00:03:10.380 --> 00:03:11.970
to the sound of a
person's voice--

00:03:11.970 --> 00:03:14.442
not just what you're saying,
but the actual quality

00:03:14.442 --> 00:03:16.400
of your voice can sometimes
make the difference

00:03:16.400 --> 00:03:17.964
between success and failure.

00:03:17.964 --> 00:03:19.380
This is part of
the message that I

00:03:19.380 --> 00:03:22.034
want to pass on-- that I have
been passing on for some time.

00:03:22.034 --> 00:03:23.450
MALE SPEAKER: And
[INAUDIBLE] what

00:03:23.450 --> 00:03:25.870
is your vision for your work?

00:03:25.870 --> 00:03:27.880
GARY CATONA: The more
I teach, the more I

00:03:27.880 --> 00:03:30.185
realize how important
the voice is.

00:03:30.185 --> 00:03:30.810
Think about it.

00:03:30.810 --> 00:03:31.610
We all speak.

00:03:31.610 --> 00:03:32.395
We all love music.

00:03:32.395 --> 00:03:33.430
We all love singers.

00:03:33.430 --> 00:03:36.590
Yet it's the one field where
we don't think enough about.

00:03:36.590 --> 00:03:41.044
We think working out and the
proper nutrition and so on.

00:03:41.044 --> 00:03:43.460
But very few of us really think
very much about our voice.

00:03:43.460 --> 00:03:45.390
And think about how
crucial your voices are.

00:03:45.390 --> 00:03:47.056
I mean, look what
we're doing right now.

00:03:47.056 --> 00:03:49.820
We're talking, communicating.

00:03:49.820 --> 00:03:51.595
And your voice is interesting.

00:03:51.595 --> 00:03:54.440
The voice is almost a
mystical aspect of who we are.

00:03:54.440 --> 00:03:55.810
Think about it for a second.

00:03:55.810 --> 00:03:58.772
In the actual quality
of your voice, you live.

00:03:58.772 --> 00:04:01.230
Your identity, your personality,
your emotions, your moods,

00:04:01.230 --> 00:04:03.420
your feelings, all
within sound waves.

00:04:03.420 --> 00:04:05.190
But how is that possible?

00:04:05.190 --> 00:04:06.940
How could mere
sound waves capture

00:04:06.940 --> 00:04:08.710
the essence of who you are?

00:04:08.710 --> 00:04:10.360
So whenever you're
speaking, you're

00:04:10.360 --> 00:04:12.990
literally transmitting
who you are in your voice.

00:04:12.990 --> 00:04:15.660
So it stands to
reason that you should

00:04:15.660 --> 00:04:17.800
try to have the best
voice you can possibly

00:04:17.800 --> 00:04:20.740
have to express who
you are, whether it's

00:04:20.740 --> 00:04:24.244
in a personal relationship
or in your profession.

00:04:24.244 --> 00:04:25.660
MALE SPEAKER: Yeah,
and obviously,

00:04:25.660 --> 00:04:27.260
to Googlers,
elaborating on voice,

00:04:27.260 --> 00:04:30.660
that could be a unique way
of doing things in the future

00:04:30.660 --> 00:04:32.140
to create better
user experiences.

00:04:32.140 --> 00:04:35.030
And so we need to think
deeply about voice

00:04:35.030 --> 00:04:37.617
and all its technical
implications as well.

