or the aha moment that actually
says, I believe in this person,

00:12:19.980 --> 00:12:21.480
and I believe in
what they're doing,

00:12:21.480 --> 00:12:23.526
and I've seen
fundamental results.

00:12:23.526 --> 00:12:26.025
Who is the person that quote,
"discovered" you, if you will?

00:12:26.025 --> 00:12:28.080
GARY CATONA: You know,
I had those moments.

00:12:28.080 --> 00:12:30.290
It's just remarkable to
think that within the course

00:12:30.290 --> 00:12:32.790
of a year and a half, I had
four people who discovered me,

00:12:32.790 --> 00:12:33.920
so to speak.

00:12:33.920 --> 00:12:37.500
Any one of whom would have done
it, but I had four at once.

00:12:37.500 --> 00:12:40.340
And probably the most profound
one was Shirley MacLaine.

00:12:40.340 --> 00:12:43.500
She was about to go on
tour with Frank Sinatra.

00:12:43.500 --> 00:12:45.920
And she wasn't a singer, really.

00:12:45.920 --> 00:12:48.634
And she heard about me
through another student.

00:12:48.634 --> 00:12:51.050
And out of the clear blue sky,
I got a phone call one day.

00:12:51.050 --> 00:12:53.070
I'm living in this one-bedroom
apartment in Hollywood,

00:12:53.070 --> 00:12:55.370
hardly making any income
whatsoever, and just wondering

00:12:55.370 --> 00:12:56.680
what I'm going to do next.

00:12:56.680 --> 00:12:58.315
Next thing I know, the phone
rings, it's Shirley MacLaine.

00:12:58.315 --> 00:13:00.810
And she said to me, what
are you doing in one hour?

00:13:00.810 --> 00:13:02.484
I said, let me see here.

00:13:02.484 --> 00:13:03.192
Uh, I'm free.

00:13:03.192 --> 00:13:04.400
She says, I'll be right over.

00:13:04.400 --> 00:13:07.980
She drove from Malibu to
my place in Hollywood,

00:13:07.980 --> 00:13:09.397
and I started
giving her a lesson.

00:13:09.397 --> 00:13:11.396
And within 10 minutes
after giving her a lesson,

00:13:11.396 --> 00:13:13.160
she said, you're
going on tour with me.

00:13:13.160 --> 00:13:19.076
And from her came Tony Bennett,
Liza Minnelli, Andy Williams.

00:13:19.076 --> 00:13:21.010
And then I went on tour
with her and Sinatra,

00:13:21.010 --> 00:13:23.642
and that was a whole
'nother story altogether.

00:13:23.642 --> 00:13:25.600
MALE SPEAKER: So at the
beginning of the video,

00:13:25.600 --> 00:13:28.350
we heard a beautiful,
familiar voice.

00:13:28.350 --> 00:13:31.720
What was it like working
with Whitney Houston?

00:13:31.720 --> 00:13:32.740
GARY CATONA: Boy.

00:13:32.740 --> 00:13:35.637
Imagine working with one the
greatest voices of all time.

00:13:35.637 --> 00:13:37.220
And what's interesting
psychologically

00:13:37.220 --> 00:13:42.260
is when you teach somebody
that you admired as a fan.

00:13:42.260 --> 00:13:42.969
Think about that.

00:13:42.969 --> 00:13:45.051
Imagine somebody that you--
whether it's in sports

00:13:45.051 --> 00:13:45.587
or whatever.

00:13:45.587 --> 00:13:47.920
And before you know it, the
person is sitting before you

00:13:47.920 --> 00:13:50.020
and saying, show
me how to do this.

00:13:50.020 --> 00:13:52.060
One of the greatest
voices of all time.

00:13:52.060 --> 00:13:56.470
She is the embodiment of--
she has so many vocal virtues,

00:13:56.470 --> 00:14:02.000
it's hard to discuss them,
besides her beautiful tone,

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:05.630
her strong voice, her amazing
range, her inherent musicality.

00:14:05.630 --> 00:14:07.540
It was a wonderful experience.

00:14:07.540 --> 00:14:09.470
And she responded very,
very, very quickly

00:14:09.470 --> 00:14:11.270
to my vocal exercises.

00:14:11.270 --> 00:14:12.770
MALE SPEAKER: Now
when great singers

00:14:12.770 --> 00:14:16.755
like Andrea Bocelli, Tony
Bennett, Steven Tyler--

00:14:16.755 --> 00:14:20.810
one of my all-time favorites--
they're putting their trust

00:14:20.810 --> 00:14:23.320
in you with their
voices, their livelihood.

00:14:23.320 --> 00:14:25.240
That's an immense
responsibility.

00:14:25.240 --> 00:14:27.510
What's that like?

00:14:27.510 --> 00:14:29.400
The burden, there's
a certain burden

00:14:29.400 --> 00:14:31.890
and a certain weight
that goes with that.

00:14:31.890 --> 00:14:33.390
GARY CATONA: Well,
it's interesting.

00:14:33.390 --> 00:14:35.056
You have to-- for
people with those kind

00:14:35.056 --> 00:14:37.680
of large personalities,
your first goal

00:14:37.680 --> 00:14:40.624
is to convince that person that
you know what you're doing.

00:14:40.624 --> 00:14:43.040
Because they're used to telling
everybody else what to do.

00:14:43.040 --> 00:14:45.807
So here you are, standing
in front of a superstar,

00:14:45.807 --> 00:14:47.640
and you have to tell
that person what to do,

00:14:47.640 --> 00:14:50.520
and that person has to
listen without compromise.

00:14:50.520 --> 00:14:52.610
Because if the person
doesn't listen,

00:14:52.610 --> 00:14:54.950
the results are not
there, and then you fail.

00:14:54.950 --> 00:14:56.870
So one of my first
goals is to convince

00:14:56.870 --> 00:14:59.510
the person what I do is real.

00:14:59.510 --> 00:15:02.512
And the way I do that is
demonstrate with my own voice

00:15:02.512 --> 00:15:03.970
different kinds of
exercises, and I

00:15:03.970 --> 00:15:05.720
have a pretty strong voice.

00:15:05.720 --> 00:15:09.240
And once they heard
my voice, then they're

00:15:09.240 --> 00:15:11.070
open, more available
to being taught.

00:15:11.070 --> 00:15:13.220
And luckily, my
results are fast,

00:15:13.220 --> 00:15:15.130
so when I began
to work with them,

00:15:15.130 --> 00:15:18.640
they heard the results in
their voices very quickly.

00:15:18.640 --> 00:15:22.270
And before you know it,
they're devoted students.

00:15:22.270 --> 00:15:25.200
MALE SPEAKER: Now working with
that diverse group of singers

00:15:25.200 --> 00:15:28.350
and entertainers and other
notable public figures, what

00:15:28.350 --> 00:15:30.520
was the common thread,
the common denominator,

00:15:30.520 --> 00:15:33.880
or common note, if you would,
that you saw between them?

00:15:33.880 --> 00:15:37.860
Was there such an element
that you could identify?

00:15:37.860 --> 00:15:39.610
GARY CATONA: Yeah, I
think the people that

00:15:39.610 --> 00:15:42.460
are really successful
in this field,

00:15:42.460 --> 00:15:45.805
they have a lot of
personality characteristics

00:15:45.805 --> 00:15:49.030
that are in common, one
of which is that they have

00:15:49.030 --> 00:15:51.800
a determination
to be successful,

00:15:51.800 --> 00:15:55.600
and nothing will stop them,
and they have no other choice.

00:15:55.600 --> 00:15:58.502
When I have a student that
says to me, if I don't make it

00:15:58.502 --> 00:16:00.280
as a singer, I'll
go to law school--

00:16:00.280 --> 00:16:02.710
when I hear that, I normally
say, please go to law school.

00:16:02.710 --> 00:16:05.960
Because you have to
have almost an obsession

00:16:05.960 --> 00:16:07.120
to be this kind of person.

00:16:07.120 --> 00:16:09.110
Because think about it.

00:16:09.110 --> 00:16:11.720
It's a desire to have the
whole world look at you

00:16:11.720 --> 00:16:13.290
and say, look how
wonderful you are.

00:16:13.290 --> 00:16:14.590
Look how great you are.

00:16:14.590 --> 00:16:17.250
And if you're a real artist,
if you have real talent,

00:16:17.250 --> 00:16:19.540
you have a major
impact on the world.

00:16:19.540 --> 00:16:21.890
That's what being a performer
can do and being a singer

00:16:21.890 --> 00:16:22.637
can do.

00:16:22.637 --> 00:16:23.470
MALE SPEAKER: Great.

00:16:23.470 --> 00:16:25.690
Well, I want to transition
here to your vision

00:16:25.690 --> 00:16:29.240
that you mention upfront from
voice builder to the stars

00:16:29.240 --> 00:16:31.630
to the voice builder
of the world.

00:16:31.630 --> 00:16:34.080
So let's talk about
reaching beyond singers.

00:16:34.080 --> 00:16:37.076
You've worked with a
wide range of people.

00:16:37.076 --> 00:16:38.700
One of the things
that I was intrigued,

00:16:38.700 --> 00:16:40.510
when I was reading
about your bio,

00:16:40.510 --> 00:16:42.640
was that you helped
Muhammad Ali and Jack

00:16:42.640 --> 00:16:45.540
Klugman, who were suffering
from vocal disorders.

00:16:45.540 --> 00:16:47.640
Can you tell us a
little bit how you

00:16:47.640 --> 00:16:49.710
went beyond singing
and entertainers

00:16:49.710 --> 00:16:51.750
into helping people
that may have

00:16:51.750 --> 00:16:54.584
a medical issue or
other injury type issue?

00:16:54.584 --> 00:16:56.000
GARY CATONA: What's
interesting is

00:16:56.000 --> 00:16:58.950
that my initial interest
in developing my system

00:16:58.950 --> 00:17:01.430
was to work with singers,
but my first successes

00:17:01.430 --> 00:17:03.693
were with people with
vocal difficulties.

00:17:03.693 --> 00:17:05.859
And I became very well known
throughout the country,

00:17:05.859 --> 00:17:08.210
in fact, the world,
by returning people

00:17:08.210 --> 00:17:09.656
with damaged speaking voices.

00:17:09.656 --> 00:17:11.030
And Muhammad Ali
was one of them.

00:17:11.030 --> 00:17:13.579
He had Parkinson's
syndrome, which

00:17:13.579 --> 00:17:16.190
causes the voice, the
slur, and the voice

00:17:16.190 --> 00:17:17.810
to get very, very weak.

00:17:17.810 --> 00:17:20.460
And by doing the exercises,
his voice got stronger.

00:17:20.460 --> 00:17:22.630
And then you saw Jack
Klugman in the video.

00:17:22.630 --> 00:17:23.920
He had throat cancer.

00:17:23.920 --> 00:17:25.720
He had his throat irradiated.

00:17:25.720 --> 00:17:27.880
And they took off one
vocal cord and replaced it

00:17:27.880 --> 00:17:29.140
with a prosthetic.

00:17:29.140 --> 00:17:31.430
So when I got his
voice, he had nothing.

00:17:31.430 --> 00:17:33.350
So for me, I wasn't
really sure whether I

00:17:33.350 --> 00:17:35.590
could help the guy out,
to be honest with you.

00:17:35.590 --> 00:17:37.960
But during the course
of a few months,

00:17:37.960 --> 00:17:42.490
his voice returned
very effectively.

00:17:42.490 --> 00:17:45.580
MALE SPEAKER: And there
was another person

00:17:45.580 --> 00:17:47.705
you worked with, a jazz
guitarist, Larry Carlton.

00:17:47.705 --> 00:17:48.830
GARY CATONA: Larry Carlton.

00:17:48.830 --> 00:17:51.040
MALE SPEAKER: Who basically
suffered a severe gunshot

00:17:51.040 --> 00:17:52.070
wound to the throat?

00:17:52.070 --> 00:17:53.236
GARY CATONA: That's correct.

00:17:53.236 --> 00:17:55.110
MALE SPEAKER: And if
I recall, basically

00:17:55.110 --> 00:17:57.227
was left with one
functioning vocal cord,

00:17:57.227 --> 00:17:58.560
and the other one was paralyzed.

00:17:58.560 --> 00:18:00.350
How do you work with
somebody like that

00:18:00.350 --> 00:18:01.920
on an injury that's
that in depth?

00:18:01.920 --> 00:18:03.420
GARY CATONA: It's
quite a challenge.

00:18:03.420 --> 00:18:06.380
Because when you
sing or speak, you

00:18:06.380 --> 00:18:08.850
need to close the
glottis in the throat.

00:18:08.850 --> 00:18:10.370
That causes the
cords to vibrate.

00:18:10.370 --> 00:18:10.870
Right?

00:18:10.870 --> 00:18:13.860
Everybody knows that who
understands music and singing.

00:18:13.860 --> 00:18:15.610
What happens if
one is paralyzed?

00:18:15.610 --> 00:18:17.568
How do you have-- because
when one's paralyzed,

00:18:17.568 --> 00:18:21.010
that means when the person
speaks, rather than doing this,

00:18:21.010 --> 00:18:23.300
that happens, and
all the air escapes.

00:18:23.300 --> 00:18:24.760
That was my challenge.

00:18:24.760 --> 00:18:27.910
So my whole process is
based upon exercise.

00:18:27.910 --> 00:18:30.077
Now, how do you exercise
a voice with only one cord

00:18:30.077 --> 00:18:30.660
that's moving?

00:18:30.660 --> 00:18:33.500
Well, this is how I did it,
through experimentation.

00:18:33.500 --> 00:18:35.090
Here's what I found.

00:18:35.090 --> 00:18:37.720
I would ask Larry
to change pitch.

00:18:37.720 --> 00:18:39.758
And this was his
voice, basically.

00:18:39.758 --> 00:18:43.640
[RASPING] That was his voice.

00:18:43.640 --> 00:18:45.140
That's the voice I
had to deal with.

00:18:45.140 --> 00:18:46.181
So here's what I noticed.

00:18:46.181 --> 00:18:48.320
When I had him change
pitch, on certain pitches,

00:18:48.320 --> 00:18:50.659
the breath would
increase in pitch.

00:18:50.659 --> 00:18:52.450
I'd hear this-- [BREATH
CHANGING IN PITCH].

00:18:54.990 --> 00:18:57.150
That told me that there
was some kind of movement

00:18:57.150 --> 00:18:59.470
in the vocal mechanism
that caused the breath

00:18:59.470 --> 00:19:00.720
pitch to rise.

00:19:00.720 --> 00:19:02.970
So what I did is I
stayed on that pitch,

00:19:02.970 --> 00:19:06.830
and slowly but surely, I
heard this-- [RASPING].

00:19:06.830 --> 00:19:08.940
Before I know it, the
voice began coming back,

00:19:08.940 --> 00:19:10.670
and the whole voice returned.

00:19:10.670 --> 00:19:13.080
What happened was
the one functioning

00:19:13.080 --> 00:19:15.390
vocal fold overcompensated
for the one that

00:19:15.390 --> 00:19:17.976
was paralyzed and,
past the midline,

00:19:17.976 --> 00:19:21.370
had made contact with the
one that wasn't moving.

00:19:21.370 --> 00:19:23.960
So he had the strongest
vocal cord in the world.

00:19:26.720 --> 00:19:29.240
MALE SPEAKER: So that raises
an interesting point, again,

00:19:29.240 --> 00:19:31.670
this vision of voice
builder to the world.

00:19:31.670 --> 00:19:33.570
Can anyone learn your technique?

00:19:33.570 --> 00:19:36.600
Can it be somebody that's a
public speaker at Toastmasters?

00:19:36.600 --> 00:19:37.837
Could it be a young child?

00:19:37.837 --> 00:19:39.920
Is there a certain age
that you would or would not

00:19:39.920 --> 00:19:42.370
teach this particular
technique, or does it basically

00:19:42.370 --> 00:19:43.420
apply to anybody?

00:19:43.420 --> 00:19:46.290
GARY CATONA: Anybody
could use this process.

00:19:46.290 --> 00:19:49.575
I use the analogy of
being like a sport,

00:19:49.575 --> 00:19:52.250
because singing and using
your voice is athletic,

00:19:52.250 --> 00:19:55.610
and it's based upon the use of
muscles in the vocal mechanism.

00:19:55.610 --> 00:19:58.275
So if you have the
proper kind of exercises,

00:19:58.275 --> 00:19:59.400
you can develop your voice.

00:19:59.400 --> 00:20:01.750
Now, everybody, no matter
how tone deaf some of you

00:20:01.750 --> 00:20:05.060
might think you are, all of
you have musical ability.

00:20:05.060 --> 00:20:07.849
You recognize rhythms,
and you hear patterns,

00:20:07.849 --> 00:20:09.640
and you remember music,
and you like music.

00:20:09.640 --> 00:20:11.455
So music is a part of our DNA.

00:20:11.455 --> 00:20:13.020
That's how we're hard-wired.

00:20:13.020 --> 00:20:14.820
We love music.

00:20:14.820 --> 00:20:18.000
The problem is transferring
the experience of music

00:20:18.000 --> 00:20:20.380
to the physical
process of singing.

00:20:20.380 --> 00:20:22.340
And what that requires
is the vocal mechanism,

00:20:22.340 --> 00:20:24.136
which is made of
muscles, to correspond

00:20:24.136 --> 00:20:25.510
to when you're
hearing something.

00:20:25.510 --> 00:20:27.670
So if I hear [HUMMING],
I have a [HUMMING].

00:20:27.670 --> 00:20:29.170
That means what I'm
hearing and what

00:20:29.170 --> 00:20:30.517
I'm producing are the same note.

00:20:30.517 --> 00:20:32.350
When you build your
voice, what you're doing

00:20:32.350 --> 00:20:35.310
is you're increasing the
ability of the vocal muscles

00:20:35.310 --> 00:20:36.970
to respond to what
you're hearing.

00:20:36.970 --> 00:20:40.170
So you develop what I call
ear-throat coordination.

00:20:40.170 --> 00:20:43.670
And that's why virtually anybody
who undergoes this process

00:20:43.670 --> 00:20:46.220
could develop a singing voice.

00:20:46.220 --> 00:20:48.400
MALE SPEAKER: So when
you say the process,

00:20:48.400 --> 00:20:51.810
how do you see, beyond the
interaction we had just there,

00:20:51.810 --> 00:20:53.620
but how do you see
technology playing

00:20:53.620 --> 00:20:56.940
an enabling force for you
to achieve your vision?

00:20:56.940 --> 00:20:59.260
How are you going to
reach out to the world

00:20:59.260 --> 00:21:02.182
and teach the world these
types of techniques?

00:21:02.182 --> 00:21:03.890
How do you see technology
playing a part?

00:21:03.890 --> 00:21:05.348
GARY CATONA:
Technology is crucial.

00:21:05.348 --> 00:21:07.690
For example, in my case, I
have a voice building app

00:21:07.690 --> 00:21:10.210
that people use, that's
called Voice Builder, that

00:21:10.210 --> 00:21:12.140
actually builds people's voices.

00:21:12.140 --> 00:21:14.500
It's not as good as being
in front of a live teacher,

00:21:14.500 --> 00:21:16.160
but it works very, very well.

00:21:16.160 --> 00:21:18.130
And with the wonder
of the internet,

00:21:18.130 --> 00:21:20.900
I teach through Skype,
sometimes, for example.

00:21:20.900 --> 00:21:23.794
And technology
itself, we're going

00:21:23.794 --> 00:21:25.460
to start a voice
building academy, which

00:21:25.460 --> 00:21:30.100
will be a one on one interactive
school where we're teaching

00:21:30.100 --> 00:21:34.355
a number of, maybe, 100 people
at once to undergo the voice

00:21:34.355 --> 00:21:36.080
building process.

00:21:36.080 --> 00:21:38.800
So technology is
crucial in realizing

00:21:38.800 --> 00:21:40.386
what I see my goal,
my vision to be.

00:21:40.386 --> 00:21:42.510
MALE SPEAKER: And this can
be a mobile application.

00:21:42.510 --> 00:21:44.090
People can do it
wherever they're at,

00:21:44.090 --> 00:21:46.410
whatever platform they
may be on in the future.

00:21:46.410 --> 00:21:46.700
GARY CATONA: Yes.

00:21:46.700 --> 00:21:47.533
MALE SPEAKER: Great.

00:21:47.533 --> 00:21:50.370
Now, I know you used
Hangouts with my son.

00:21:50.370 --> 00:21:53.000
And it was great to see
that interaction technology

00:21:53.000 --> 00:21:55.250
to bring together you,
in a remote place,

00:21:55.250 --> 00:21:58.280
teaching my son voice
building exercises,

00:21:58.280 --> 00:22:02.750
and the clarity with which you
can hear his pitch and voice

00:22:02.750 --> 00:22:04.020
was extraordinary.

00:22:04.020 --> 00:22:04.847
So it had a--

00:22:04.847 --> 00:22:06.305
GARY CATONA: I
worked with his son,

00:22:06.305 --> 00:22:08.059
who has a vocal difficulty.

00:22:08.059 --> 00:22:09.600
And over the course
of a few minutes,

00:22:09.600 --> 00:22:12.770
his voice began returning and
had a very strong response

00:22:12.770 --> 00:22:14.010
to it.

00:22:14.010 --> 00:22:16.360
MALE SPEAKER: You couldn't
see us, but off the camera--

00:22:16.360 --> 00:22:18.930
he didn't see us-- there was
tears in his parents' eyes.

00:22:18.930 --> 00:22:22.350
That's the first time we heard
his voice come out like that.

00:22:22.350 --> 00:22:25.420
Being that you approached
it from a different angle,

00:22:25.420 --> 00:22:27.940
you wrote a book called
"Revolution in Singing."

00:22:27.940 --> 00:22:29.440
What is that book all about?

00:22:29.440 --> 00:22:32.070
When you say revolution,
what do you mean by that.?

00:22:32.070 --> 00:22:33.720
GARY CATONA: Well,
what I did was

00:22:33.720 --> 00:22:36.690
I-- the book was about
the history of singing

00:22:36.690 --> 00:22:39.010
in general, how,
where it originated,

00:22:39.010 --> 00:22:41.115
some salient singers
throughout history that

00:22:41.115 --> 00:22:45.260
have made a profound impact,
like Caruso and Frank Sinatra

00:22:45.260 --> 00:22:47.570
and Paul McCartney and all
of these various singers

00:22:47.570 --> 00:22:49.910
that have made such an
impact on our culture.

00:22:49.910 --> 00:22:53.620
But also, I go through the
principles of great singing.

00:22:53.620 --> 00:22:56.520
I talk about how I
developed my process,

00:22:56.520 --> 00:23:00.190
and I try to overcome-- there
are a number of misconceptions

00:23:00.190 --> 00:23:02.869
about the voice
that are preventing

00:23:02.869 --> 00:23:04.410
many, many singers
that are naturally

00:23:04.410 --> 00:23:05.410
talented from becoming great.

00:23:05.410 --> 00:23:06.930
There are people
in this room that

00:23:06.930 --> 00:23:11.060
would have great voices if
you underwent this process,

00:23:11.060 --> 00:23:13.510
and if you would let
go the old concepts.

00:23:13.510 --> 00:23:16.620
For example, if you're told
that you're stuck with the voice

00:23:16.620 --> 00:23:20.560
you're born with-- you're told
this, and that's not true.

00:23:20.560 --> 00:23:22.720
Because the voice is
composed of muscles,

00:23:22.720 --> 00:23:25.217
you literally can
build your voice.

00:23:25.217 --> 00:23:27.550
The voice that you speak with
is not your natural voice.

00:23:27.550 --> 00:23:30.560
It's the voice that has
evolved over time based

00:23:30.560 --> 00:23:33.706
upon your childhood experiences
and your psychological

00:23:33.706 --> 00:23:35.830
characteristics and whether
or not you're a singer.

00:23:35.830 --> 00:23:39.052
So the voice that you
have is an adapted sound,

00:23:39.052 --> 00:23:40.510
which means you
can take that sound

00:23:40.510 --> 00:23:44.720
and build it with
the proper exercises.

00:23:44.720 --> 00:23:47.439
MALE SPEAKER: Now, when
