00:23:49.605 --> 00:23:52.040
if I recall, and actually looked
at one of the greatest opera

00:23:52.040 --> 00:23:53.825
singers of all time,
sort of as a mentor.

00:23:53.825 --> 00:23:54.450
GARY CATONA: That's right.

00:23:54.450 --> 00:23:55.770
MALE SPEAKER: And looking
at some of the techniques

00:23:55.770 --> 00:23:57.395
that he did at the
turn of the century.

00:23:57.395 --> 00:23:59.710
Can you elaborate, one,
who he was and two,

00:23:59.710 --> 00:24:02.952
what you learned from looking
at that historical perspective?

00:24:02.952 --> 00:24:05.410
GARY CATONA: The greatest opera
singer probably of all time

00:24:05.410 --> 00:24:07.201
was this gentleman
named Enrico Caruso, who

00:24:07.201 --> 00:24:10.590
was an Italian tenor,
who died in 1921.

00:24:10.590 --> 00:24:12.910
He wrote a book called
"The Art of Singing."

00:24:12.910 --> 00:24:16.180
In it, he talked about using his
throat muscles to create sounds

00:24:16.180 --> 00:24:18.470
and singing from the
back of the throat.

00:24:18.470 --> 00:24:20.895
Now, most of you don't
really understand

00:24:20.895 --> 00:24:21.770
what that might mean.

00:24:21.770 --> 00:24:23.780
But if you study
voice today, you're

00:24:23.780 --> 00:24:26.070
told to sing out of
your throat and to sing

00:24:26.070 --> 00:24:28.608
to your nasal cap, which
is called the mask.

00:24:28.608 --> 00:24:30.316
But what they teach
today is the opposite

00:24:30.316 --> 00:24:33.180
of what Caruso teaches, which is
the greatest voice of all time.

00:24:33.180 --> 00:24:35.180
So how did that ever happen?

00:24:35.180 --> 00:24:37.100
So that was a light for me.

00:24:37.100 --> 00:24:40.000
When I read-- I just said,
this is what Caruso says.

00:24:40.000 --> 00:24:41.250
We have to take him seriously.

00:24:41.250 --> 00:24:43.277
When he says, sing from
the back of the throat,

00:24:43.277 --> 00:24:45.110
how can you sing from
the back of the throat

00:24:45.110 --> 00:24:46.300
and sing in the
front-- in the mask?

00:24:46.300 --> 00:24:47.500
How do you do that
at the same time?

00:24:47.500 --> 00:24:48.780
It's not physically possible.

00:24:48.780 --> 00:24:51.320
Somebody has to be right,
and someone has to be wrong.

00:24:51.320 --> 00:24:52.700
Caruso was right.

00:24:52.700 --> 00:24:55.700
MALE SPEAKER: So you've often
talked about that he was right,

00:24:55.700 --> 00:24:57.580
but there's a field
of isokinetics.

00:24:57.580 --> 00:24:59.837
Can you tell the audience
what that's all about

00:24:59.837 --> 00:25:02.170
and how you think it directly
applies to your philosophy

00:25:02.170 --> 00:25:03.534
and approach to voice building?

00:25:03.534 --> 00:25:05.950
GARY CATONA: When I went through
the process of developing

00:25:05.950 --> 00:25:07.710
my voice building
system, I discovered

00:25:07.710 --> 00:25:11.000
a kind of exercise program
that's called isokinetics.

00:25:11.000 --> 00:25:14.920
And what I discovered
is a way of applying

00:25:14.920 --> 00:25:17.520
that form of exercise
to the vocal muscles.

00:25:17.520 --> 00:25:19.500
And I can tell you what
it is very quickly.

00:25:19.500 --> 00:25:25.160
It means taking
muscles through motion

00:25:25.160 --> 00:25:27.250
while keeping the
movement constant,

00:25:27.250 --> 00:25:30.680
while keeping the pressure
maximized at the same time.

00:25:30.680 --> 00:25:32.790
That concept builds muscles.

00:25:32.790 --> 00:25:35.140
So I discovered a
way of applying that

00:25:35.140 --> 00:25:37.510
to vocal exercises
that results in

00:25:37.510 --> 00:25:39.949
very strong, very
rapid vocal growth.

