00:27:47.420 --> 00:27:50.220
AUDIENCE: What would you say is
the most common mistake people

00:27:50.220 --> 00:27:52.580
make with their voice, that
someone off the street,

00:27:52.580 --> 00:27:54.042
when they talk to
you, you say, ah,

00:27:54.042 --> 00:27:55.250
you're doing something wrong.

00:27:55.250 --> 00:27:56.770
What would you say is
the most common mistake?

00:27:56.770 --> 00:27:58.395
GARY CATONA: For
singers in particular?

00:27:58.395 --> 00:28:00.640
AUDIENCE: For
whatever the-- yeah.

00:28:00.640 --> 00:28:03.574
GARY CATONA: Well, the
mistake-- basically

00:28:03.574 --> 00:28:05.990
first they'll have certain
misconceptions about the voice,

00:28:05.990 --> 00:28:09.380
one of which I spoke about.

00:28:09.380 --> 00:28:12.100
The fact that the voice is
fragile is a misconception.

00:28:12.100 --> 00:28:13.490
The voice is very tough.

00:28:13.490 --> 00:28:16.127
It's able to endure
a lot of stress.

00:28:16.127 --> 00:28:18.710
If you're a singer, the number
one mistake I see with singers,

00:28:18.710 --> 00:28:21.200
they sing in the wrong key.

00:28:21.200 --> 00:28:23.760
People have an obsession
with high notes

00:28:23.760 --> 00:28:26.440
to the point of causing the
larynx to-- whenever you cause

00:28:26.440 --> 00:28:28.810
the larynx to rise
unnaturally, over time,

00:28:28.810 --> 00:28:30.847
the voice begins
collapsing and develops

00:28:30.847 --> 00:28:33.430
all these vocal conditions that
you probably have heard about.

00:28:33.430 --> 00:28:37.040
Did you know that the voice
matures at the age of 35 to 40,

00:28:37.040 --> 00:28:38.090
45?

00:28:38.090 --> 00:28:41.490
Yet in the world, most people in
the rock business, for example,

00:28:41.490 --> 00:28:43.560
by that time, their
voices are gone.

00:28:43.560 --> 00:28:46.550
The very moment when their
voices should be the best,

00:28:46.550 --> 00:28:50.610
they lose it because they're
screaming out these notes

00:28:50.610 --> 00:28:53.300
and not preparing themselves
like athletes the way

00:28:53.300 --> 00:28:55.320
that they should.

00:28:55.320 --> 00:28:55.834
You got it.

00:28:55.834 --> 00:28:58.000
MALE SPEAKER: So there's
still an opportunity for me

00:28:58.000 --> 00:29:00.626
to hit the rock tour at my age?

00:29:00.626 --> 00:29:03.079
GARY CATONA: Can you move?

00:29:03.079 --> 00:29:03.870
AUDIENCE: Hi, Gary.

00:29:03.870 --> 00:29:04.911
GARY CATONA: Hello, love.

00:29:04.911 --> 00:29:08.940
AUDIENCE: So who is the
best singer in the Beatles?

00:29:08.940 --> 00:29:10.805
Who's your favorite
singer in the Beatles?

00:29:10.805 --> 00:29:11.724
Is it really Ringo?

00:29:11.724 --> 00:29:13.140
GARY CATONA: Well,
let me explain.

00:29:13.140 --> 00:29:14.790
A singer is an
interesting thing.

00:29:14.790 --> 00:29:17.852
There are three aspects
of singing, the voice,

00:29:17.852 --> 00:29:19.060
the vocalist, and the singer.

00:29:19.060 --> 00:29:21.710
Whenever-- anybody you want
to consider as a singer,

00:29:21.710 --> 00:29:24.120
think about the
three components.

00:29:24.120 --> 00:29:26.930
The vocalist is being able
to sing on pitch, having

00:29:26.930 --> 00:29:29.710
the right technique, and so on.

00:29:29.710 --> 00:29:32.090
The voice is what's
distinctive about your voice.

00:29:32.090 --> 00:29:34.350
As soon as you hear
that voice, you know it.

00:29:34.350 --> 00:29:37.240
Frank Sinatra, Barbara
Streisand, Stevie Wonder.

00:29:37.240 --> 00:29:38.990
There are people that
are great vocalists,

00:29:38.990 --> 00:29:40.670
but they don't have
the good voices

00:29:40.670 --> 00:29:43.520
because you don't
recognize who they are.

00:29:43.520 --> 00:29:47.360
They make great background
singers or jingle singers,

00:29:47.360 --> 00:29:50.119
but because they
lack the voice, they

00:29:50.119 --> 00:29:52.160
have a problem making it
as an individual artist.

00:29:52.160 --> 00:29:53.420
And then there's the singer.

00:29:53.420 --> 00:29:56.140
The singer is being
able to make people

00:29:56.140 --> 00:29:58.730
feel what you're singing about.

00:29:58.730 --> 00:30:01.890
Somebody could have a bad voice,
not being a very good vocalist,

00:30:01.890 --> 00:30:03.400
but they're very good singers.

00:30:03.400 --> 00:30:06.342
Did I mention Bob Dylan?

00:30:06.342 --> 00:30:07.800
But you see what
I'm trying to say?

00:30:07.800 --> 00:30:09.740
So whenever you
evaluate a singer,

00:30:09.740 --> 00:30:11.250
think about those
three questions.

00:30:11.250 --> 00:30:17.480
How is the person as a vocalist,
as a singer, and as a voice?

00:30:17.480 --> 00:30:19.697
So the answer to
your question, who

00:30:19.697 --> 00:30:21.030
do you think the best singer is?

00:30:21.030 --> 00:30:22.499
AUDIENCE: I always liked Paul.

00:30:22.499 --> 00:30:24.540
GARY CATONA: Do you think
Paul's the best singer?

00:30:24.540 --> 00:30:26.330
Now think about
what I just said.

00:30:26.330 --> 00:30:28.670
Is he the one-- does he make
you feel the most or not?

00:30:28.670 --> 00:30:32.360
AUDIENCE: Yeah, I'd choose Paul.

00:30:32.360 --> 00:30:34.546
GARY CATONA: I'd have to
go with Lennon, personally.

00:30:34.546 --> 00:30:36.609
AUDIENCE: So I've taken
some voice classes, too,

00:30:36.609 --> 00:30:38.650
and one of the things that
was really fascinating

00:30:38.650 --> 00:30:42.890
is if you take guitar lessons,
if you screw something up,

00:30:42.890 --> 00:30:43.930
people can see it.

00:30:43.930 --> 00:30:46.500
They say, OK, change your
position, do this, do this.

00:30:46.500 --> 00:30:49.562
It's a much easier
way of teaching

00:30:49.562 --> 00:30:50.770
because you see what's wrong.

00:30:50.770 --> 00:30:52.860
But with voice, you
really don't see

00:30:52.860 --> 00:30:56.240
a lot of what's happening in the
throat, so you have to listen,

00:30:56.240 --> 00:30:59.710
and you have to interpret what
probably this guy's doing wrong

00:30:59.710 --> 00:31:02.510
and how to-- like my vocal
teacher used to say, OK,

00:31:02.510 --> 00:31:04.080
imagine there's like
a ping pong ball

00:31:04.080 --> 00:31:05.330
at the back of your
throat, whatever.

00:31:05.330 --> 00:31:05.750
GARY CATONA: So horrible.

00:31:05.750 --> 00:31:06.416
AUDIENCE: Right?

00:31:06.416 --> 00:31:11.284
So then, clearly, you're
more successful than a lot

00:31:11.284 --> 00:31:11.950
of ther coaches.

00:31:11.950 --> 00:31:14.530
So what makes you
special in that way?

00:31:14.530 --> 00:31:17.700
Because it seems like there's
an art to it, in a sense.

00:31:17.700 --> 00:31:20.340
You kind of have to feel it
because you don't see it.

00:31:20.340 --> 00:31:22.200
GARY CATONA: Well,
the whole problem

00:31:22.200 --> 00:31:25.455
with the field of teaching,
based upon the funnel effect

00:31:25.455 --> 00:31:27.765
of human nature, is that
the voice is invisible.

00:31:27.765 --> 00:31:28.599
You can't see it.

00:31:28.599 --> 00:31:29.390
You can't touch it.

00:31:29.390 --> 00:31:30.181
You can't smell it.

00:31:30.181 --> 00:31:31.850
You can't taste it.

00:31:31.850 --> 00:31:32.880
You can barely feel it.

00:31:32.880 --> 00:31:34.510
So it happens on the inside.

00:31:34.510 --> 00:31:37.280
So there's almost like a
magical component to it.

00:31:37.280 --> 00:31:39.320
A person stands there
and opens up his voice,

00:31:39.320 --> 00:31:40.690
and all the sudden, this
amazing voice comes out.

00:31:40.690 --> 00:31:42.030
Where is it coming from?

00:31:42.030 --> 00:31:43.450
So it stands to
reason that people

00:31:43.450 --> 00:31:45.325
that are great singers
by nature don't really

00:31:45.325 --> 00:31:47.830
know how they do what they do.

00:31:47.830 --> 00:31:50.900
It's one of the downsides
of being gifted at anything.

00:31:50.900 --> 00:31:53.575
If you're a gifted runner
or a gifted tennis player,

00:31:53.575 --> 00:31:54.950
you don't know
why you're gifted.

00:31:54.950 --> 00:31:56.170
You just have it.

00:31:56.170 --> 00:31:58.880
And yet those are the very
people that end up teaching.

00:31:58.880 --> 00:32:00.287
Think about that for a second.

00:32:00.287 --> 00:32:01.620
That answers a lot of questions.

00:32:01.620 --> 00:32:04.690
How can it be that the field
of singing is in such disarray?

00:32:04.690 --> 00:32:07.520
because the people that have
the responsibility of passing

00:32:07.520 --> 00:32:10.440
on the art form have no idea
what they're talking about.

00:32:10.440 --> 00:32:12.856
They just do it by nature, and
they have to make a living,

00:32:12.856 --> 00:32:14.370
so why not teach?

00:32:14.370 --> 00:32:19.420
So you have to base upon
the vocal study on science.

00:32:19.420 --> 00:32:23.450
And in my case, it's the science
of how the vocal muscles work.

00:32:23.450 --> 00:32:27.390
What I've done is I've aligned
my exercises specifically

00:32:27.390 --> 00:32:31.720
with how the local mechanism
works on a biochemical level.

00:32:31.720 --> 00:32:34.520
And that's the only way
you should teach voice.

