00:39:25.580 --> 00:39:27.922
So he's already working on that.

00:39:27.922 --> 00:39:28.630
GARY CATONA: Yes.

00:39:28.630 --> 00:39:30.370
AUDIENCE: At the
beginning, you described

00:39:30.370 --> 00:39:31.940
that most people focus
on the diaphragm,

00:39:31.940 --> 00:39:33.523
and that you focus
on the vocal cords.

00:39:33.523 --> 00:39:35.870
Do you completely
de-emphasize the diagram?

00:39:35.870 --> 00:39:37.750
Or what's the relationship
between those two

00:39:37.750 --> 00:39:38.624
muscles in your mind?

00:39:38.624 --> 00:39:41.210
GARY CATONA: I will shock
you by telling you something.

00:39:41.210 --> 00:39:43.710
All of you have heard
this expression,

00:39:43.710 --> 00:39:45.400
sing from the diaphragm.

00:39:45.400 --> 00:39:46.700
Right?

00:39:46.700 --> 00:39:51.440
Do you know it's physically
impossible to do that?

00:39:51.440 --> 00:39:54.400
When you sing, when
you take a breath,

00:39:54.400 --> 00:39:58.520
the diaphragm drops, and
air fills up your lungs.

00:39:58.520 --> 00:40:01.240
When you breathe out,
which is when you sing,

00:40:01.240 --> 00:40:04.215
the diaphragm is disconnected,
completely disengaged.

00:40:04.215 --> 00:40:06.800
It cannot be used,
even if you wanted to.

00:40:06.800 --> 00:40:10.480
So again, one of the
confusing concepts in voice

00:40:10.480 --> 00:40:12.992
is this concept of singing
from the diaphragm.

00:40:12.992 --> 00:40:14.450
MALE SPEAKER: Yeah,
it's definitely

00:40:14.450 --> 00:40:15.783
challenging conventional wisdom.

00:40:15.783 --> 00:40:18.380
GARY CATONA: So there
are so many myths

00:40:18.380 --> 00:40:19.770
that populate the
field of voice.

00:40:19.770 --> 00:40:22.700
It's shocking.

00:40:22.700 --> 00:40:24.710
AUDIENCE: So I'm
not a singer, but I

00:40:24.710 --> 00:40:28.790
used to be a wind musician, and
I can also talk fairly loud.

00:40:28.790 --> 00:40:31.470
And I've noticed
over the years, it

00:40:31.470 --> 00:40:34.070
seems like there's definitely
a different range of volume

00:40:34.070 --> 00:40:36.290
that people either
have or can develop.

00:40:36.290 --> 00:40:38.110
And I've always felt
like people talk

00:40:38.110 --> 00:40:40.780
about the difference
between being loud and being

00:40:40.780 --> 00:40:41.789
able to project.

00:40:41.789 --> 00:40:43.830
But I've never known if
there was anything really

00:40:43.830 --> 00:40:46.454
there to that, except
I've noticed it in people.

00:40:46.454 --> 00:40:48.370
And I was wondering if
you could say something

00:40:48.370 --> 00:40:50.010
about that, either from
the science about it

00:40:50.010 --> 00:40:51.230
or what you think about that.

00:40:51.230 --> 00:40:52.080
GARY CATONA: Yes.

00:40:52.080 --> 00:40:56.102
There's certain frequencies
that travel better

00:40:56.102 --> 00:40:57.060
than other frequencies.

00:40:57.060 --> 00:41:00.712
For example, in an orchestra,
the piccolo really travels.

00:41:00.712 --> 00:41:02.170
You have to tell
the piccolo player

00:41:02.170 --> 00:41:04.390
to hold back so he
doesn't overtake.

00:41:04.390 --> 00:41:07.679
And it's a thin sound,
but the frequency carries.

00:41:07.679 --> 00:41:09.720
In singing, you have
certain kind of frequencies.

00:41:09.720 --> 00:41:14.450
There's a frequency called the
singer's format, for example.

00:41:14.450 --> 00:41:19.820
It's that part of the voice
that if I go [SINGING] hee,

00:41:19.820 --> 00:41:21.910
hee-- hear that buzz
sound in the voice?

00:41:21.910 --> 00:41:25.409
That's part of the singer's
format, which penetrates.

00:41:25.409 --> 00:41:27.950
You can have a sound that's big
but doesn't have the singer's

00:41:27.950 --> 00:41:30.840
format, which doesn't carry
as much as a voice that's

00:41:30.840 --> 00:41:33.745
smaller but with that frequency.

00:41:33.745 --> 00:41:35.495
So it's the frequency
we're talking about.

00:41:38.960 --> 00:41:40.710
AUDIENCE: I wonder
about that a little bit

00:41:40.710 --> 00:41:43.880
because, like I said, when
I was a wind musician,

00:41:43.880 --> 00:41:45.480
and I could play a
note on something,

00:41:45.480 --> 00:41:48.330
but I know a pro, like--
I was a saxophone player.

00:41:48.330 --> 00:41:50.650
So I could play
something, and Stan Getz

00:41:50.650 --> 00:41:52.600
was able to be 10 times
louder than I was.

00:41:52.600 --> 00:41:54.860
GARY CATONA: He found the
frequency that traveled.

00:41:54.860 --> 00:41:56.207
That was part of his skill.

00:41:56.207 --> 00:41:57.540
You know what I'm talking about?

00:41:57.540 --> 00:41:58.331
That's what he did.

00:41:58.331 --> 00:42:01.830
He was able to find
those frequencies that

00:42:01.830 --> 00:42:05.326
seared through everything else.

00:42:05.326 --> 00:42:06.950
AUDIENCE: I sort of
have two questions.

00:42:06.950 --> 00:42:08.570
One was a follow-on
to what you just

00:42:08.570 --> 00:42:10.780
said about not singing
from the diaphragm.

00:42:10.780 --> 00:42:14.330
Yet there has to be
pressurization because clearly,

00:42:14.330 --> 00:42:16.690
the difference between a
quiet voice and a loud voice

00:42:16.690 --> 00:42:19.820
has to do with the pressure
behind the column of air.

00:42:19.820 --> 00:42:22.930
So how do you describe that if
not singing from the diaphragm?

00:42:22.930 --> 00:42:24.210
GARY CATONA: First of all,
you sing from the throat

00:42:24.210 --> 00:42:25.918
because that's where
the vocal cords are.

00:42:25.918 --> 00:42:26.930
That's the first part.

00:42:26.930 --> 00:42:28.709
The cords are not
located in your stomach.

00:42:28.709 --> 00:42:30.000
They're located in your throat.

00:42:30.000 --> 00:42:32.640
Secondly, breath is
crucial to singing.

00:42:32.640 --> 00:42:35.165
But what controls the breath
are the vocal cords, not

00:42:35.165 --> 00:42:36.790
the other way around.

00:42:36.790 --> 00:42:39.630
When you speak, the
vocal folds close,

00:42:39.630 --> 00:42:41.050
and the breath is blocked.

00:42:41.050 --> 00:42:43.650
And the way the
vocal cords behave

00:42:43.650 --> 00:42:46.250
determines how the
breath is maneuvered.

00:42:46.250 --> 00:42:48.530
We have it in
reverse, mistakenly.

00:42:48.530 --> 00:42:50.580
We have the breath
controlling the vocal cords,

00:42:50.580 --> 00:42:52.510
which doesn't work that way.

00:42:52.510 --> 00:42:54.790
And I noticed this when
I began teaching people

00:42:54.790 --> 00:42:56.140
with vocal problems.

00:42:56.140 --> 00:42:58.137
Many of them would
have no breath.

00:42:58.137 --> 00:43:00.220
They'd speak, and often,
their breath would leave.

00:43:00.220 --> 00:43:02.219
And you'd say, well, the
problem with the person

00:43:02.219 --> 00:43:03.240
is a breathing problem.

00:43:03.240 --> 00:43:05.730
By stretching the vocal folds,
all the sudden, not only

00:43:05.730 --> 00:43:08.220
does the breath come back,
but the voice comes back.

00:43:08.220 --> 00:43:12.056
So by making the vocal cords
stronger and more coordinated,

00:43:12.056 --> 00:43:14.285
it literally causes
the voice to be

00:43:14.285 --> 00:43:15.660
produced in a more
efficient way.

00:43:15.660 --> 00:43:18.300
So the emphasis
is on the throat.

00:43:18.300 --> 00:43:20.505
That controls the breath,
not the other way around.

00:43:20.505 --> 00:43:21.880
AUDIENCE: And the
other thing is,

00:43:21.880 --> 00:43:25.947
you were talking earlier
about vocal strain.

00:43:25.947 --> 00:43:27.780
And I was wondering if
you could talk at all

00:43:27.780 --> 00:43:31.630
about the transitions of
chest voice and head voice.

00:43:31.630 --> 00:43:34.920
GARY CATONA: Yeah, one of the
important concepts in singing

00:43:34.920 --> 00:43:37.480
is moving from one
register to the next.

00:43:37.480 --> 00:43:39.110
And it's been the
bone of contention

00:43:39.110 --> 00:43:40.970
for a long, long time.

00:43:40.970 --> 00:43:42.930
And there are various
exercises that

00:43:42.930 --> 00:43:44.840
